04186nam a22006255i 9781447322580DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20162016xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781447322580  a(DE-B1597)647199  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0470002bisacsh04a306.8741 aHendrick, Harry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNarcissistic Parenting in an Insecure World :bA History of Parenting Culture 1920s to Present /cHarry Hendrick. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbout the author -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tThe origins of social democracy’s family ideal: 1920s–1940s -- tThe re-imagining of adult–child relations between the wars -- tWartime influences: from the evacuation to the Children Act 1948 -- tCharacteristics of the ‘Golden Age’: 1940s–early 1970s -- tRebuilding the family: 1940s–1950s -- tThe ‘long sixties’: 1958–1974 -- tInfluences and examples from the USA -- tSocial science and American liberalism -- tParental narcissism in neoliberal times: 1970s to the present -- tAspects of neoliberalism: political, economic and social realignments -- tLaying the foundations for parental narcissism -- tThe New Labour era, and beyond: narcissism comes of age -- tTherapeutic reflections -- tNarcissism and the ‘politics of recognition’: concepts of the late-modern self -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this provocative history of parenting, Harry Hendrick analyses the social and economic reasons behind parenting trends. He shows how broader social changes, including neoliberalism, feminism, the collapse of the social-democratic ideal, and the 'new behaviourism', have led to the rise of the anxious and narcissistic parent. The book charts the shift from the liberal and progressive parenting styles of the 1940s-70s, to the more 'behavioural', punitive and managerial methods of childrearing today, made popular by 'experts' such as Gina Ford and Supernanny Jo Frost, and by New Labour's parent education programmes. This trend, Hendrick argues, is symptomatic of the sour, mean-spirited and vindictive social norms found throughout society today. It undermines the better instincts of parents and, therefore, damages parent-child relations. Instead, he proposes, parents should focus on understanding and helping their children as they work at growing up.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aNarcissismxHistoryy20th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aParent and childxHistoryy20th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aParentingxHistoryy20th centuryzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311119643540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447322580423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447322580/original  a978-3-11-119643-5  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK